"1766","1401":"1401","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1451":"1451","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1758":"1758","England":"Anglie","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, Anglie","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Anglie","Kettleborough, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Anglie"},"da":{"1382–1412":"1382–1412","1758–1766":"1758–1766","1392–1451":"1392–1451","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1340–1401":"1340–1401","1350–1401":"1350–1401","1766":"1766","1401":"1401","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1451":"1451","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1758":"1758","England":"England","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Kettleborough, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"1382–1412":"1382–1412","1758–1766":"1758–1766","1392–1451":"1392–1451","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1340–1401":"1340–1401","1350–1401":"1350–1401","1766":"1766","1401":"1401","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1451":"1451","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1758":"1758","England":"England","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Kettleborough, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1382–1412":"1382–1412","1758–1766":"1758–1766","1392–1451":"1392–1451","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1340–1401":"1340–1401","1350–1401":"1350–1401","1766":"1766","1401":"1401","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1451":"1451","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1758":"1758","England":"England","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Kettleborough, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Charles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Antoine, Andre, Francois, Patrice, Germaine, Magalie, Philippe, Yves, Alain, Jacques, Cecile.","French, Welsh, English, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and African (mainly Tanzania): from the French form of the ancient Germanic personal name   Karl   ‘man, husband, freeman’, which was Latinized as <i>Carolus</i>. In France the personal name was popular from an early date, due to the fame of the Emperor Charlemagne (<i>c.</i> 742–814; Latin name <i>Carolus Magnus</i>, i.e. Charles the Great). The Old French form <i>Charles</i> was briefly introduced to England by the Normans, but was rare during the main period of surname formation. It was introduced more successfully to Scotland in the 16th century by the Stuarts, who had strong ties with France, and was brought by them to England in the 17th century. Its frequency as a Welsh surname is attributable to the late date of Welsh surname formation. Old English <i>Ceorl</i> ‘peasant’ is also found as a byname, but the resulting Middle English form, <i>Charl</i>, with a patronymic in <i>-s</i>, if it existed at all, would have been absorbed by the French form introduced by the Normans. English variants pronounced with initial <i>k-</i> for the most part reflect the cognate Old Norse personal name <i>Karl</i>, <i>Karli</i>. Compare   Carl  .","English: in some cases, possibly a habitational name from Charles (Devon), or a post-medieval variant of <b>Cherrill</b>, with excrescent <i>-s</i>, perhaps by false association with the personal name <i>Charles</i>. <b>Cherrill</b> is either a habitational name from Cherhill in Wilshire, or a status name from Middle English <i>cherl</i>, <i>cheril</i>, <i>charl</i>, <i>chirl</i> ‘churl, bonded tenant, serf; peasant’."],"variants":[{"name":"Carlino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carlo, Mario, Antonio, Dino, Elio, Francesco, Giusto, Pasquale, Rocco, Carmelo, Ciro, Liborio, Salvadore, Carmella, Emilio, Ernesto, Isidoro.","Italian: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Carlo</i>, an equivalent of   Charles  . <i>Carlino</i> was also a term denoting a medieval Italian coin, and it is possible that in some cases the surname arose as a nickname, possibly for a worthless fellow, since it was a coin of low value, or as an occupational name for a moneyer."]},{"name":"Karl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Lothar, Erwin, Erhard, Georg, Otto, Bernd, Bernhard, Ernst, Gerhard, Hartmut, Heinz.","German: from the German personal name <i>Karl</i>, from Old High German <i>karl</i> ‘man, husband, freeman’. The popularity of this name and its cognates in central and northern Europe was greatly enhanced by its status as a royal and imperial name; in particular it was bestowed in honor of the Frankish emperor Charlemagne (about 742–814; Latin name <i>Carolus Magnus</i>). This surname is also found in some other European countries, e.g. in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Croatia, but is relatively rare there. See also   Carl   and   Charles  ."]},{"name":"Carleo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Luigi, Armando, Gino, Nino, Rocco, Xavier.","Italian:","from the medieval Greek personal name <i>Kaloleon</i>or <i>Kaloleos</i> meaning ‘Leon the good’."]},{"name":"Carles","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Bienvenido, Blanca, Carlito, Cristina, Elva, Ernesto, Humberto, Juan Carlos, Mariana, Mariano.  French Emile, Alain, Marcel.","Catalan: from the personal name <i>Carles</i>, Catalan form of   Charles  .","French: regional variant of   Charles  ; compare 1 above."]},{"name":"Carlisi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Annamaria, Antonio, Salvatore.","Italian: from a diminutive, <i>Carlino</i>, of the personal name <i>Carlo</i>, an equivalent of   Charles  ."]},{"name":"Carlo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Juan, Julio, Luis, Orlando, Ricardo, Aida, Alicia, Andres, Angel.  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Silvio, Antonio, Carmela, Salvatore.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Carlo</i>, an equivalent of   Charles  ."]},{"name":"Carlozzi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Carlo, Emidio, Enrico, Giuseppe.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Carlozzo</i>, a derivative of <i>Carlo</i>, an equivalent of   Charles  ."]},{"name":"Carlos","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Francisco, Raul, Alicia, Jesus, Luis, Armando, Jaime, Carlos, Ruben.  Portuguese Fernandes, Joao, Joaquim.","Spanish and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Carlos</i>, an equivalent of   Charles  ."]},{"name":"Carolus","meanings":["Dutch (mainly Groningen) and German: from the personal name <i>Carolus</i>, Latinized form of ancient Germanic name <i>Karl</i> (see   Charles  ), or a Latinized (humanistic) form of the surname   Karl   or   Carl  . This surname is also established in South Africa."]},{"name":"Carlone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carlo, Umberto, Angelo, Antonio, Biaggio, Corrado, Cosmo, Filippo, Gaetano, Giuseppe, Nichola, Pasquale.","Italian: from an augmentative of the personal name <i>Carlo</i>, an equivalent of   Charles  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":0,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe'